Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Remove the puff pastry from your fridge.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Chop the @baking potato{1}(chopped into 2cm chunks, no need to peel) into 2cm chunks.

Unroll the @puff pastry sheet{1}(keeping its baking paper) and lay it onto a #baking tray{}. Using a #knife{}, score a 2cm border all around - be careful not to cut all the way through. Prick the pastry inside the border all over with a #fork{}.

When the oven is hot, bake the pastry on the top shelf until starting to colour and puff up, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{10-15%minutes}.

In the meantime, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}, and grate the @mature cheddar cheese{90%g}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @sugar{1/2}. Stir-fry until softened and browned, ~{10-15%minutes}. Lower the heat as necessary.

Meanwhile, pick the leaves from their stalks and roughly chop the @mint{1}(leaves picked and stalks discarded) (discard the stalks). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(grated) (or use a garlic press).

Pop the @tikka masala paste{75%g} and @tomato puree{30%g} into a small #bowl{}. Season with salt, sugar (see ingredients for amount) and @pepper{}, mix together, then set the tikka sauce aside.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the saucepan. Mix in the browned onions, @peas{120%g}, garlic and @North Indian style spice mix{1}. Season with salt and pepper.

Once the pastry has baked, remove it from the oven. Push down the centre with the back of a #spoon{}.

Use the spoon to gently spread the tikka sauce over the base of the tart, keeping within the border.

Scatter the cheese over the sauce, then top with an even layer of the potato mixture.

Return the tart to the top shelf of your oven to bake until golden brown, ~{7-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a small bowl, combine the @mango chutney{40%g} with half the mint.

Once the tart is ready, top with dollops of the mint mango chutney and sprinkle over the remaining mint.

Slice up your samosa tart, then share between your plates. Enjoy!

> Our Limited Edition Samosa Tart and Mint Mango Chutney is a delicious veggie option that makes it easy to eat more veg in your diet and try something new!